50|$|Increasing {{unemployment}} due to {{the subprime}} mortgage crisis of 2008-2010 has significantly reduced the amount of payroll tax income <b>that</b> funds <b>Social</b> <b>Security.</b> Further, the crisis also caused more to apply for both retirement and disability benefits than expected. During 2009, payroll taxes and taxation of benefits resulted in cash revenues of $689.2 billion, while payments totaled $685.8 billion, resulting in a cash surplus (excluding interest) of $3.4 billion. Interest of $118.3 billion meant <b>that</b> the <b>Social</b> <b>Security</b> Trust Fund overall increased by $121.7 billion (i.e., the cash surplus plus interest). The 2009 cash surplus of $3.4 billion was a significant reduction from the $63.9 billion cash surplus of 2008.|$|R
